{"cursor":"3221","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox disease\n | Name = Myelopathy Image = Caption = DiseasesDB = 22984 ICD10 = ICD9 = ICDO =\n | OMIM = MedlinePlus = eMedicineSubj = eMedicineTopic = MeshID = D013118\n}} 'Myelopathy' refers to pathology of the spinal cord. When due to\ntrauma, it is known as spinal cord injury. When inflammatory, it is known as\nmyelitis. Disease that is vascular in nature is known as vascular myelopathy.\n\nClinical signs and symptoms depend on which spinal cord level (cervical,\nthoracic or lumbar) is affected and the extent (anterior, posterior or lateral)\nof the pathology, and may include:\n* upper motor neuron signs (weakness, spasticity, clumsiness, altered tonus)\n* pathological hyperreflexia and inverted Plantar reflex (positive\n  Babinski sign)\n* sensory deficits\n* bowel/bladder symptoms and sexual dysfunction.\n\nDifferential diagnosis of chronic myelopathy is\nextensive. [http://www.myelopathyweb.com/index.html Myelopathy differential\ndiagnosis web site]\n\nThe presence and severity of myelopathy can be evaluated by means of\nTranscranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS), a neurophysiological method that\nallows the measurement of the time required for a neural impulse to cross the\npyramidal tracts, starting from the cerebral cortex and ending at the anterior\nhorn cells of the cervical, thoracic or lumbar spinal cord. This measurement\nis called Central Conduction Time (CCT). TMS can aid physicians to: Chen\nR, Cros D, Curra A, Di Lazzaro V, Lefaucheur JP, Magistris MR, Mills K, RÃ¶sler\nKM, Triggs WJ, Ugawa Y, Ziemann U. The clinical diagnostic utility of\ntranscranial magnetic stimulation: report of an IFCN committee. Clin\nNeurophysiol. 2008 Mar;119(3):504-32.\n\n* determine whether myelopathy exists\n* identify the level of the spinal cord where myelopathy is located. This is\n  especially useful in cases where more than two lesions may be responsible for\n  the clinical symptoms and signs, such as in patients with two or more cervical\n  disc hernias\n* follow-up the progression of myelopathy in time, for example before and after\n  cervical spine surgery\n\nTMS can also help in the differential diagnosis of different causes of pyramidal\ntract damage.\n","linknr":334,"url":"Myelopathy","recorded":1375692420,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Myelopathy&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Myelopathy&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myelopathy","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/International_Statistical_Classification_of_Diseases_and_Related_Health_Problems","/wiki/ICD-10","/wiki/ICD-10_Chapter_G","http://apps.who.int/classifications/icd10/browse/2010/en#/G95","/wiki/International_Statistical_Classification_of_Diseases_and_Related_Health_Problems","/wiki/List_of_ICD-9_codes","http://www.icd9data.com/getICD9Code.ashx?icd9=336.9","/wiki/Diseases_Database","http://www.diseasesdatabase.com/ddb22984.htm","/wiki/Medical_Subject_Headings","http://www.nlm.nih.gov/cgi/mesh/2013/MB_cgi?field=uid&term=D013118","/wiki/Spinal_cord","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Physic